  "original_title": "\u0dc4\u0ddc\u0d82\u0d9a\u0ddc\u0d82 \u0db1\u0dc0 \u0db4\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0db0\u0dcf\u0db1 \u0dc0\u0dd2\u0db0\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a \u0dbd\u0dd3 \u0daf\u0dd2\u0dc0\u0dd4\u0dbb\u0dd4\u0db8\u0dca \u0daf\u0dd9\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Hong Kong swears in new chief executive Lee",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "John Lee was sworn in before Chinese President Xi Jinping as the sixth-term chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government on Friday morning, marking the 25th anniversary of Hong Kong's reunification with China.",
        "In his speech, Lee expressed his gratitude to the central government and promised to build \"a more caring and united Hong Kong as a land full of vitality, hope and opportunities for development.\"",
        "As a special administrative region under \"One Country, Two Systems\", Hong Kong enjoys unique advantages, and as the most effective gateway between the country and the world, Hong Kong can fully integrate into China's national development, develop and serve as a metropolis with high international connectivity. He said. Lee also called on Hong Kong people to join hands for a brighter future.",
        "\"Together, we will begin a new chapter in building a better Hong Kong, contribute to Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and stability, and contribute to the realization of the Chinese dream of national rejuvenation.\""
      ],
